The XPS spectrum of the TFN-PS-CDs membrane further confirmed the presence of sulfonate groups by showing an S 2p peak at 164.0 eV in comparison with those of the TFC and TFN-PEI-CDs membranes (Fig. 3b). The small deviation in the sulfur concentrations measured (0.04% vs 0.69%) at different positions on three membrane samples indirectly indicate the homogeneous dispersion of PS-CDs in the polyamide matrix (Table 2
                        ) at the micrometer scale (the measurement area). Unfortunately, the same conclusion cannot be drawn for the PEI-CDs as they comprise the same elements as the polyamide matrix. Moreover, the elemental concentrations obtained from the XPS results determined the degree of crosslinking of the polyamide selective layer following the trend: TFC > TFN-PEI-CDs > TFN-PS-CDs (Table 2). Note that the concentrations of oxygen and nitrogen elements contributed by PS-CDs were ruled out for the calculation based on the S 2p signal detected in both the membrane and carbon dots samples, while the concentration of oxygen contributed by PEI-CDs is expected to be negligible (see Section 2.7 for details). The high-resolution elemental spectra were deconvoluted to obtain the chemical bonds and their concentrations in the membranes (Fig. S8). The increased concentrations of the OC–O (from unreacted acyl chloride groups in TMC) and N–H bonds (from unreacted amine groups in PIP and/or PEI-CDs) from the TFC to the TFN-PEI-CDs and TFN-PS-CDs membranes also verified the loosened polyamide selective layer by the carbon dots (Table 3
                        ) [46,47]. The nearly identical concentrations of S–O/S–C and SO bonds (corresponding to the S 2p3/2 and S 2p1/2 spin-orbital splitting at 164.0 and 165.2 eV, respectively [48]) in the TFN-PS-CDs membrane to those in PS-CDs assure the creation of sulfonate group-based nanovoids by the carbon dots in the surface layer of the membrane (the XPS technique has a detection depth of only a few nanometers).
